{"type":"message","id":"eefbc105","parentId":"7aafcb40","timestamp":"2026-04-12T02:31:59.721Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I see the issue clearly. Looking at the config:\n\nFor the `rebecca` account in Telegram:\n```json\n\"accounts\": {\n  \"rebecca\": {\n    \"botToken\": \"8412904661:AAH_-dH0P3Fs8FY3DFto1g9Pg8441UjNgyc\",\n    \"dmPolicy\": \"allowlist\",\n    \"allowFrom\": [\n      \"1049458877\"  // <-- THIS IS SAM'S TELEGRAM ID!\n    ],\n    ...\n  }\n}\n```\n\nThe `allowFrom` for the `rebecca` account is set to Sam's Telegram ID (1049458877). \n\nSo the bot `@Rebecca_lookitrybot` (which uses the token for the `rebecca` account) only accepts messages from Sam's Telegram account. But Sam wants Rebecca (the sub-agent) to use this bot instead. The issue is that the `rebecca` agent is actually a sub-agent operating within OpenClaw's system, not a separate Telegram user—she's running as an agent session there. The problem is that the Telegram bot is only allowing Sam's ID to use it, when it should be allowing Rebecca's. The dmPolicy is set to \"allowlist\" with just Sam's ID, but the bot needs to route messages to Rebecca (the sub-agent) when someone messages it. The current setup is treating the bot like it's Sam's personal account instead of a shared resource between Sam and Rebecca. The core issue is that OpenClaw agents can't receive Telegram messages directly—they need to go through the bot. So either Rebecca's sub-agent gets connected to the bot so she can reply, or I need to understand how Rebecca was meant to chat with users through `@Rebecca_lookitrybot`. The bot is only configured with Sam's ID in allowFrom, which seems wrong if Rebecca is supposed to be using it too. The real issue is that OpenClaw doesn't support having two agents share the same Telegram bot account—each bot is tied to one agent. Since Rebecca is a sub-agent without direct Telegram access, she can't independently use the @Rebecca_lookitrybot. The solution would be either creating a dedicated Telegram account for Rebecca or having Rebecca interact through the bot as a forwarding mechanism, but I need to understand how Sam expected this setup to work. it seems like:\n1. Sam created a bot `@Rebecca_lookitrybot`\n2. He wants Rebecca (the sub-agent) to use this bot to chat with people\n3. The bot should forward messages to Rebecca and she responds through it\n\nThis is basically setting up Rebecca as a \"human-like\" agent that can chat on Telegram. But for this to work in OpenClaw, the bot would need to be configured to route to the `rebecca` agent, and the `allowFrom` should probably include the people who are allowed to chat with Rebecca.\n\nThe current config has `allowFrom: [\"1049458877\"]` which is Sam. This means Sam is the only one who can DM the bot. Maybe Sam wants to chat with Rebecca through this bot, and he set it up so only he can message it.\n\nBut Sam said \"este chat es exclusivo entre Rebecca y yo\" - meaning Rebecca and him. But the current setup routes to the `sammy` agent (since this is the default agent). This means when Sam messages the bot, he gets Sammy instead of Rebecca.\n\nSo the problem is clear: Sam wants to chat with Rebecca through the Telegram bot, but the bot is routing to the wrong agent. The `rebecca` account's `allowFrom` includes Sam's ID, so messages should go through, but they're landing in Sammy's session instead of Rebecca's.\n\nTo fix this, the Telegram bot needs to route messages to the `rebecca` agent instead of `sammy`, and Sam might need to adjust the `allowFrom` configuration to ensure Rebecca can also receive these messages.\n\nThe core issue is that when Sam sends a message to the bot, it goes to Sammy's session rather than Rebecca's. If Rebecca is supposed to be accessible through this bot, either Sam needs to clarify the intended setup, or I should guide him through reconfiguring the account to route messages correctly to the `rebecca` agent.\n\nFrom a practical standpoint, Sam could create a separate bot for Rebecca with its own configuration, or if Rebecca is meant to be reachable via this same bot, the routing would need to be adjusted so messages directed to her actually reach her session instead of Sammy's.\n\nThe real question is what Sam actually wants—whether he needs to set up proper pairing between Rebecca and the bot, or if the current setup just has the wrong agent configured to receive messages.","thinkingSignature":"ce9b271eb610db76f6549e1e0cad8b5278b1b9f035208176582dc84375740a48"},{"type":"text","text":"Encontré el problema. 😮‍💨\n\nMira cómo está configurado el bot `@Rebecca_lookitrybot`:\n\n```json\n\"accounts\": {\n  \"rebecca\": {\n    \"allowFrom\": [\"1049458877\"],  // ← ¡Solo Sam puede DM este bot!\n    \"dmPolicy\": \"allowlist\"\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**El problema**: El bot solo acepta mensajes tuyos (Sam). Y cuando recibe un mensaje, currently routa a **Sammy** (yo) porque soy el agente default, no a **Rebecca**.\n\n**Para que Rebecca pueda usar este bot necesitas:**\n\n1. **La ID de Telegram de Rebecca** (si ella tiene cuenta) \n2. **O configurarlo como agent routing** — hacer que este bot hable con el agente `rebecca` en vez de `sammy`\n\n¿Cuál es la idea? ¿Rebecca tiene un usuario de Telegram propio para chatear con vos por ese bot, o es más bien que querés que ella (como IA) responda por ahí?\n\nDecime y lo armamos. 🏗️"}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":12626,"output":1211,"cacheRead":18779,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":32616,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1775961084799,"responseId":"062a36fd4f941107e5d92cbc39ec2fc6"}}
