{"type":"message","id":"96760540","parentId":"f0cc299a","timestamp":"2026-04-12T02:33:42.658Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"34\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"1049458877\",\n  \"sender\": \"Wilkie Devs & Design\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Sat 2026-04-11 21:33 GMT-5\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"Wilkie Devs & Design (1049458877)\",\n  \"id\": \"1049458877\",\n  \"name\": \"Wilkie Devs & Design\",\n  \"username\": \"WilkieDevs\"\n}\n```\n\nHazlo quiero hablar directamente con su agente"}],"timestamp":1775961222656}}
{"type":"message","id":"3c9cc7f9","parentId":"96760540","timestamp":"2026-04-12T02:34:19.513Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Sam wants to talk directly with Rebecca's agent. The issue is:\n\n1. The bot `@Rebecca_lookitrybot` is configured with `allowFrom: [\"1049458877\"]` which is Sam's Telegram ID\n2. Currently this routes to Sammy (default agent)\n3. We need to either:\n   a) Change the routing so that this bot talks to the `rebecca` agent instead of the default `sammy`\n   b) Or configure the agentId mapping for this bot\n\nLooking at the config, I don't see a direct \"routing to agent\" field. Let me think about how OpenClaw routes DM messages... \n\nActually, I think the way OpenClaw works with Telegram accounts is that each bot token maps to an \"account\" and by default all DMs go to the default agent unless there's a specific routing configured.\n\nBut wait - looking at the \"authorized senders\" in my system prompt at the top:\n```\n## Authorized Senders\nAuthorized senders: 1049458877. These senders are allowlisted; do not assume they are the owner.\n```\n\nSo 1049458877 is Sam's ID and it's authorized. But I'm (Sammy) the one responding. For Rebecca to be the agent, the bot needs to route to the `rebecca` agent, not `sammy`.\n\nLet me check if there's an agentId or similar routing field. Looking at the config... I don't see one explicitly. Maybe there's a way to specify which agent handles which account.\n\nActually, I think the issue might be simpler - the bot token for rebecca IS the @Rebecca_lookitrybot. When someone DMs this bot, OpenClaw receives it. But OpenClaw is routing to the DEFAULT agent (sammy) instead of the rebecca agent.\n\n\nThe accounts section in OpenClaw config doesn't have an explicit agentId routing field, so I might need to add a `routeToAgent` or similar field to the account config. Alternatively, the pairing or session mechanism might handle how messages get routed to different agents—maybe Rebecca has her own session and the system needs to know which agent to invoke based on the bot token being used.\n\nThe simplest approach might be to just attempt the fix: change the bot to route to the `rebecca` agent instead of defaulting to `sammy`. I should patch the config to add the agent routing, though I'm not certain what field name OpenClaw actually uses for this.\n\nLooking at the config structure more carefully, I see the agents are defined with `id`, `name`, and `workspace` fields. But I don't see an `accountId` or similar mapping that would link a Telegram bot to a specific agent. I'm considering whether the `dmPolicy: \"allowlist\"` setting might be relevant to how messages get routed, or if there's another field I'm missing that controls which agent handles incoming messages from a particular bot.\n\nThe fact that Sam can currently reach me (Sammy) through this DM suggests the routing might be working through some implicit mechanism—perhaps OpenClaw has a fallback where it defaults to the primary agent when no explicit routing is configured. To get Rebecca handling these messages instead, I might need to either change the default agent or find where OpenClaw allows specifying which agent should respond to a given Telegram account's DMs.\n\nI'm going to try patching the configuration with a `defaultAgentId` field set to \"rebecca\" on the Telegram account settings, though I'm uncertain if that's the correct field name—OpenClaw's documentation would clarify this, but I don't have immediate access to verify the exact schema.\n\nLet me patch the config and restart the gateway to see if this resolves the issue. The account `rebecca` with bot token `8412904661:AAH_-dH0P3Fs8FY3DFto1g9Pg8441UjNgyc` should route to agent `rebecca` if my assumption about how `defaultAgentId` works is correct.","thinkingSignature":"2749d785bfe33d1809ea8fdce334ad6616e2c1b4d9b918f2a92cb728dd906d8a"},{"type":"text","text":"Dale, voy a cambiar el routing para que `@Rebecca_lookitrybot` hable directo con **Rebecca** en vez de conmigo.\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_3onkqq0fx3pw_1","name":"gateway","arguments":{"action":"config.schema.lookup","path":"channels.telegram.accounts"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":107,"output":901,"cacheRead":23227,"cacheWrite":8201,"totalTokens":32436,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775961222658,"responseId":"062a378631432476b8513da40ada72ba"}}
