{"type":"message","id":"e544925f","parentId":"6fccac02","timestamp":"2026-04-12T02:34:43.486Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see `defaultTo` field! That might be what I need. Let me also check `dms` and `direct` to understand the routing. Let me look at what `defaultTo` does - it might route to a specific agent.\n\nAlso there's `dms` which might have agent routing inside it.\n\nLet me search for `defaultTo` in the docs to understand what it does.","thinkingSignature":"84d588ee82d3356ab2bd28c14dae16981aca99fd17f6c798d4f3ccd777206210"},{"type":"text","text":"Encontré el campo `defaultTo` y `dms` — voy a revisar cómo se usan para rutear al agente correcto.\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_8ou4alf4j7p5_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"grep -r \"defaultTo\\|dms.*agent\\|direct.*agent\" /home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/ 2>/dev/null | head -30"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":18563,"output":172,"cacheRead":18779,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":37514,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775961277004,"responseId":"062a37bd60dca0cdb175875e7be41d69"}}
{"type":"message","id":"ba5d6374","parentId":"e544925f","timestamp":"2026-04-12T02:34:43.651Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_8ou4alf4j7p5_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/install/ansible.md:The gateway runs directly on the host (not in Docker), but agent sandboxes use Docker for isolation. See [Sandboxing](/gateway/sandboxing) for details.\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/tools/acp-agents.md:- `cwd` (optional): requested runtime working directory (validated by backend/runtime policy). If omitted, ACP spawn inherits the target agent workspace when configured; missing inherited paths fall back to backend defaults, while real access errors are returned.\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/tools/exec-approvals.md:- Telegram approvers can be explicit (`execApprovals.approvers`) or inferred from existing owner config (`allowFrom`, plus direct-message `defaultTo` where supported)\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/tools/subagents.md:  - OpenClaw tries direct `agent` delivery first with a stable idempotency key.\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/tools/thinking.md:- Resolution order: inline directive, then session override, then per-agent default (`agents.list[].reasoningDefault`), then fallback (`off`).\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/tools/music-generation.md:For direct synchronous contexts without a session-backed agent run, the built-in\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/tools/music-generation.md:- No-session fallback: direct/local contexts without a real agent session still run inline and return the final audio result in the same turn.\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/concepts/agent.md:OpenClaw uses a single agent workspace directory (`agents.defaults.workspace`) as the agent’s **only** working directory (`cwd`) for tools and context.\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/concepts/agent.md:On the first turn of a new session, OpenClaw injects the contents of these files directly into the agent context.\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/concepts/system-prompt.md:- **Workspace**: working directory (`agents.defaults.workspace`).\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/concepts/models.md:agent directory (default `~/.openclaw/agents/<agentId>/agent/models.json`). This file\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/concepts/active-memory.md:| `config.transcriptDir`      | `string`                                                                                             | Relative blocking memory sub-agent transcript directory under the agent sessions folder                |\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/concepts/multi-agent.md:- **State directory** (`agentDir`) for auth profiles, model registry, and per-agent config.\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/concepts/multi-agent.md:You can route **different WhatsApp DMs** to different agents while staying on **one WhatsApp account**. Match on sender E.164 (like `+15551234567`) with `peer.kind: \"direct\"`. Replies still come from the same WhatsApp number (no per‑agent sender identity).\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/concepts/multi-agent.md:Important detail: direct chats collapse to the agent’s **main session key**, so true isolation requires **one agent per person**.\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/help/environment.md:| `OPENCLAW_HOME`        | Override the home directory used for all internal path resolution (`~/.openclaw/`, agent dirs, sessions, credentials). Useful when running OpenClaw as a dedicated service user. |\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/help/troubleshooting.md:   [/gateway/troubleshooting#local-openai-compatible-backend-passes-direct-probes-but-agent-runs-fail](/gateway/troubleshooting#local-openai-compatible-backend-passes-direct-probes-but-agent-runs-fail)\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/help/faq.md:    Yes, via **multi-agent routing**. Bind each sender's WhatsApp **DM** (peer `kind: \"direct\"`, sender E.164 like `+15551234567`) to a different `agentId`, so each person gets their own workspace and session store. Replies still come from the **same WhatsApp account**, and DM access control (`channels.whatsapp.dmPolicy` / `channels.whatsapp.allowFrom`) is global per WhatsApp account. See [Multi-Agent Routing](/concepts/multi-agent) and [WhatsApp](/channels/whatsapp).\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/help/faq.md:    Yes. Add extra directories via `skills.load.extraDirs` in `~/.openclaw/openclaw.json` (lowest precedence). Default precedence is `<workspace>/skills` → `<workspace>/.agents/skills` → `~/.agents/skills` → `~/.openclaw/skills` → bundled → `skills.load.extraDirs`. `clawhub` installs into `./skills` by default, which OpenClaw treats as `<workspace>/skills` on the next session. If the skill should only be visible to certain agents, pair that with `agents.defaults.skills` or `agents.list[].skills`.\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/help/faq.md:    Native installs land in the active workspace `skills/` directory. For shared skills across agents, place them in `~/.openclaw/skills/<name>/SKILL.md`. If only some agents should see a shared install, configure `agents.defaults.skills` or `agents.list[].skills`. Some skills expect binaries installed via Homebrew; on Linux that means Linuxbrew (see the Homebrew Linux FAQ entry above). See [Skills](/tools/skills), [Skills config](/tools/skills-config), and [ClawHub](/tools/clawhub).\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/help/faq.md:    Setup walkthrough + example config: [Groups: personal DMs + public groups](/channels/groups#pattern-personal-dms-public-groups-single-agent)\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/help/faq.md:    want a repo to be the default working directory, point that agent's\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/automation/standing-orders.md:Standing orders are defined in your [agent workspace](/concepts/agent-workspace) files. The recommended approach is to include them directly in `AGENTS.md` (which is auto-injected every session) so the agent always has them in context. For larger configurations, you can also place them in a dedicated file like `standing-orders.md` and reference it from `AGENTS.md`.\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/gateway/security/index.md:| `tools.exec.safe_bin_trusted_dirs_risky`                      | warn          | `safeBinTrustedDirs` includes mutable or risky directories                           | `tools.exec.safeBinTrustedDirs`, `agents.list[].tools.exec.safeBinTrustedDirs`                       | no       |\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/gateway/security/index.md:- Keep filesystem roots narrow: avoid broad roots like your home directory for agent workspaces/sandbox workspaces. Broad roots can expose sensitive local files (for example state/config under `~/.openclaw`) to filesystem tools.\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/gateway/troubleshooting.md:## Local OpenAI-compatible backend passes direct probes but agent runs fail\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/gateway/troubleshooting.md:- direct tiny requests succeed, but OpenClaw agent runs fail with backend/model\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/gateway/troubleshooting.md:4. If tiny direct requests keep passing while OpenClaw agent turns still crash\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/gateway/troubleshooting.md:- `heartbeat skipped` with `reason=dm-blocked` → heartbeat target resolved to a DM-style destination while `agents.defaults.heartbeat.directPolicy` (or per-agent override) is set to `block`.\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/gateway/configuration-reference.md:**`docker.binds`** mounts additional host directories; global and per-agent binds are merged."}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":153,"aggregated":"/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/install/ansible.md:The gateway runs directly on the host (not in Docker), but agent sandboxes use Docker for isolation. See [Sandboxing](/gateway/sandboxing) for details.\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/tools/acp-agents.md:- `cwd` (optional): requested runtime working directory (validated by backend/runtime policy). If omitted, ACP spawn inherits the target agent workspace when configured; missing inherited paths fall back to backend defaults, while real access errors are returned.\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/tools/exec-approvals.md:- Telegram approvers can be explicit (`execApprovals.approvers`) or inferred from existing owner config (`allowFrom`, plus direct-message `defaultTo` where supported)\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/tools/subagents.md:  - OpenClaw tries direct `agent` delivery first with a stable idempotency key.\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/tools/thinking.md:- Resolution order: inline directive, then session override, then per-agent default (`agents.list[].reasoningDefault`), then fallback (`off`).\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/tools/music-generation.md:For direct synchronous contexts without a session-backed agent run, the built-in\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/tools/music-generation.md:- No-session fallback: direct/local contexts without a real agent session still run inline and return the final audio result in the same turn.\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/concepts/agent.md:OpenClaw uses a single agent workspace directory (`agents.defaults.workspace`) as the agent’s **only** working directory (`cwd`) for tools and context.\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/concepts/agent.md:On the first turn of a new session, OpenClaw injects the contents of these files directly into the agent context.\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/concepts/system-prompt.md:- **Workspace**: working directory (`agents.defaults.workspace`).\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/concepts/models.md:agent directory (default `~/.openclaw/agents/<agentId>/agent/models.json`). This file\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/concepts/active-memory.md:| `config.transcriptDir`      | `string`                                                                                             | Relative blocking memory sub-agent transcript directory under the agent sessions folder                |\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/concepts/multi-agent.md:- **State directory** (`agentDir`) for auth profiles, model registry, and per-agent config.\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/concepts/multi-agent.md:You can route **different WhatsApp DMs** to different agents while staying on **one WhatsApp account**. Match on sender E.164 (like `+15551234567`) with `peer.kind: \"direct\"`. Replies still come from the same WhatsApp number (no per‑agent sender identity).\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/concepts/multi-agent.md:Important detail: direct chats collapse to the agent’s **main session key**, so true isolation requires **one agent per person**.\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/help/environment.md:| `OPENCLAW_HOME`        | Override the home directory used for all internal path resolution (`~/.openclaw/`, agent dirs, sessions, credentials). Useful when running OpenClaw as a dedicated service user. |\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/help/troubleshooting.md:   [/gateway/troubleshooting#local-openai-compatible-backend-passes-direct-probes-but-agent-runs-fail](/gateway/troubleshooting#local-openai-compatible-backend-passes-direct-probes-but-agent-runs-fail)\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/help/faq.md:    Yes, via **multi-agent routing**. Bind each sender's WhatsApp **DM** (peer `kind: \"direct\"`, sender E.164 like `+15551234567`) to a different `agentId`, so each person gets their own workspace and session store. Replies still come from the **same WhatsApp account**, and DM access control (`channels.whatsapp.dmPolicy` / `channels.whatsapp.allowFrom`) is global per WhatsApp account. See [Multi-Agent Routing](/concepts/multi-agent) and [WhatsApp](/channels/whatsapp).\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/help/faq.md:    Yes. Add extra directories via `skills.load.extraDirs` in `~/.openclaw/openclaw.json` (lowest precedence). Default precedence is `<workspace>/skills` → `<workspace>/.agents/skills` → `~/.agents/skills` → `~/.openclaw/skills` → bundled → `skills.load.extraDirs`. `clawhub` installs into `./skills` by default, which OpenClaw treats as `<workspace>/skills` on the next session. If the skill should only be visible to certain agents, pair that with `agents.defaults.skills` or `agents.list[].skills`.\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/help/faq.md:    Native installs land in the active workspace `skills/` directory. For shared skills across agents, place them in `~/.openclaw/skills/<name>/SKILL.md`. If only some agents should see a shared install, configure `agents.defaults.skills` or `agents.list[].skills`. Some skills expect binaries installed via Homebrew; on Linux that means Linuxbrew (see the Homebrew Linux FAQ entry above). See [Skills](/tools/skills), [Skills config](/tools/skills-config), and [ClawHub](/tools/clawhub).\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/help/faq.md:    Setup walkthrough + example config: [Groups: personal DMs + public groups](/channels/groups#pattern-personal-dms-public-groups-single-agent)\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/help/faq.md:    want a repo to be the default working directory, point that agent's\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/automation/standing-orders.md:Standing orders are defined in your [agent workspace](/concepts/agent-workspace) files. The recommended approach is to include them directly in `AGENTS.md` (which is auto-injected every session) so the agent always has them in context. For larger configurations, you can also place them in a dedicated file like `standing-orders.md` and reference it from `AGENTS.md`.\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/gateway/security/index.md:| `tools.exec.safe_bin_trusted_dirs_risky`                      | warn          | `safeBinTrustedDirs` includes mutable or risky directories                           | `tools.exec.safeBinTrustedDirs`, `agents.list[].tools.exec.safeBinTrustedDirs`                       | no       |\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/gateway/security/index.md:- Keep filesystem roots narrow: avoid broad roots like your home directory for agent workspaces/sandbox workspaces. Broad roots can expose sensitive local files (for example state/config under `~/.openclaw`) to filesystem tools.\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/gateway/troubleshooting.md:## Local OpenAI-compatible backend passes direct probes but agent runs fail\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/gateway/troubleshooting.md:- direct tiny requests succeed, but OpenClaw agent runs fail with backend/model\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/gateway/troubleshooting.md:4. If tiny direct requests keep passing while OpenClaw agent turns still crash\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/gateway/troubleshooting.md:- `heartbeat skipped` with `reason=dm-blocked` → heartbeat target resolved to a DM-style destination while `agents.defaults.heartbeat.directPolicy` (or per-agent override) is set to `block`.\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/gateway/configuration-reference.md:**`docker.binds`** mounts additional host directories; global and per-agent binds are merged.","cwd":"/home/travis/Lookitry/Lookitry/sammy"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775961283649}}
{"type":"message","id":"fb000403","parentId":"ba5d6374","timestamp":"2026-04-12T02:34:52.669Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The docs mention multi-agent routing for WhatsApp. Let me look more at the Telegram-specific docs for multi-agent routing. The `direct` option for WhatsApp uses `peer.kind: \"direct\"` to route to different agents. There might be a similar pattern for Telegram.Let me search for Telegram multi-agent routing specifically.","thinkingSignature":"190f84d24cd1309b5332630d1d5114a63460c3c2e83099ac89ae6e8c6154000e"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_9mrutax6x8t1_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"grep -r \"telegram.*agent\\|agent.*telegram\\|dms.*route\\|direct.*telegram\" /home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/ 2>/dev/null | head -30"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":20477,"output":136,"cacheRead":18779,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":39392,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775961283653,"responseId":"062a37c346746a86f777364e093475f5"}}
{"type":"message","id":"ea09f11e","parentId":"fb000403","timestamp":"2026-04-12T02:34:52.736Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_9mrutax6x8t1_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/tools/agent-send.md:openclaw agent --agent ops --message \"Alert\" --deliver --reply-channel telegram --reply-to \"@admin\"\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/concepts/multi-agent.md:    { agentId: \"main\", match: { channel: \"telegram\", accountId: \"default\" } },\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/concepts/multi-agent.md:    { agentId: \"alerts\", match: { channel: \"telegram\", accountId: \"alerts\" } },\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/concepts/multi-agent.md:    { agentId: \"opus\", match: { channel: \"telegram\" } },\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/help/faq.md:    openclaw agent --message \"Hello from local bot\" --deliver --channel telegram --reply-to <chat-id>\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/channels/telegram.md:    Each topic then has its own session key: `agent:zu:telegram:group:-1001234567890:topic:3`\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/channels/telegram.md:    - On VPS hosts with unstable direct egress/TLS, route Telegram API calls through `channels.telegram.proxy`:\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/channels/telegram.md:  - `channels.telegram.groups.<id>.topics.<threadId>.*`: per-topic overrides (group fields + topic-only `agentId`).\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/channels/telegram.md:  - `channels.telegram.groups.<id>.topics.<threadId>.agentId`: route this topic to a specific agent (overrides group-level and binding routing).\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/channels/telegram.md:- `channels.telegram.direct.<id>.topics.<threadId>.agentId`: route DM topics to a specific agent (same behavior as forum topics).\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/channels/telegram.md:- `channels.telegram.execApprovals.approvers`: Telegram user IDs allowed to approve or deny exec requests. Optional when `channels.telegram.allowFrom` or a direct `channels.telegram.defaultTo` already identifies the owner.\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/channels/telegram.md:- `channels.telegram.execApprovals.agentFilter`: optional agent ID filter for forwarded approval prompts.\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/channels/telegram.md:- `channels.telegram.reactionLevel`: `off | ack | minimal | extensive` — control agent's reaction capability (default: `minimal` when not set).\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/channels/channel-routing.md:- `agent:main:telegram:group:-1001234567890:topic:42`\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/channels/channel-routing.md:    { match: { channel: \"telegram\", peer: { kind: \"group\", id: \"-100123\" } }, agentId: \"support\" },\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/cli/sessions.md:openclaw sessions cleanup --enforce --active-key \"agent:main:telegram:direct:123\"\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/cli/agents.md:openclaw agents add ops --workspace ~/.openclaw/workspace-ops --bind telegram:ops --non-interactive\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/cli/agents.md:openclaw agents bind --agent work --bind telegram:ops\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/cli/agents.md:openclaw agents unbind --agent work --bind telegram:ops\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/cli/agents.md:openclaw agents bind --agent work --bind telegram:ops --bind discord:guild-a\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/cli/agents.md:openclaw agents bind --agent work --bind telegram\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/cli/agents.md:openclaw agents bind --agent work --bind telegram:ops\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/cli/agents.md:openclaw agents unbind --agent work --bind telegram:ops"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":57,"aggregated":"/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/tools/agent-send.md:openclaw agent --agent ops --message \"Alert\" --deliver --reply-channel telegram --reply-to \"@admin\"\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/concepts