s reaction capability (default: `minimal` when not set).\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/channels/channel-routing.md:- `agent:main:telegram:group:-1001234567890:topic:42`\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/channels/channel-routing.md:    { match: { channel: \"telegram\", peer: { kind: \"group\", id: \"-100123\" } }, agentId: \"support\" },\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/cli/sessions.md:openclaw sessions cleanup --enforce --active-key \"agent:main:telegram:direct:123\"\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/cli/agents.md:openclaw agents add ops --workspace ~/.openclaw/workspace-ops --bind telegram:ops --non-interactive\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/cli/agents.md:openclaw agents bind --agent work --bind telegram:ops\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/cli/agents.md:openclaw agents unbind --agent work --bind telegram:ops\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/cli/agents.md:openclaw agents bind --agent work --bind telegram:ops --bind discord:guild-a\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/cli/agents.md:openclaw agents bind --agent work --bind telegram\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/cli/agents.md:openclaw agents bind --agent work --bind telegram:ops\n/home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/cli/agents.md:openclaw agents unbind --agent work --bind telegram:ops","cwd":"/home/travis/Lookitry/Lookitry/sammy"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775961292734}}
{"type":"message","id":"a1bad921","parentId":"ea09f11e","timestamp":"2026-04-12T02:35:09.373Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand. There's a concept called \"binding\" where you bind an agent to a specific Telegram account. Let me look at the `channels.telegram.direct` routing and the `agentId` routing.\n\nFrom the docs:\n- `channels.telegram.direct.<id>.topics.<threadId>.agentId`: route DM topics to a specific agent\n- `channels.telegram.groups.<id>.topics.<threadId>.agentId`: route this topic to a specific agent\n\nAnd from multi-agent.md:\n```\n{ agentId: \"alerts\", match: { channel: \"telegram\", accountId: \"alerts\" } }\n```\n\nSo the routing can be done via:\n1. `channels.telegram.accounts.<accountId>` - for routing to a specific agent per account\n2. Or using the `agents bind` command\n\nLet me check what `openclaw agents bind` does and how to configure it via config.\n\nActually, looking at the architecture docs again:\n```json\n{ agentId: \"main\", match: { channel: \"telegram\", accountId: \"default\" } },\n```\n\nSo it seems like there's a `match` + `agentId` approach. But I'm not seeing a `match` field in the current config for `channels.telegram.accounts.rebecca`.\n\nWait, let me re-read. It seems like the account-level routing might just work - when you have an account named `rebecca`, maybe there's a way to bind that to the `rebecca` agent?\n\nActually I think the issue might be simpler. Let me look at `openclaw agents bind` to understand how it works.\n\nActually, thinking about it more simply - the `accountId` in the config is `rebecca`, and there's an agent with `id: \"rebecca\"`. Maybe OpenClaw automatically routes messages from the `rebecca` account to the `rebecca` agent?\n\n\nBut that would mean Sam would already be talking to Rebecca, not me. Since he's reaching me, something's off with the automatic routing. Let me check the Telegram binding docs more carefully - there might be a specific `agentId` field in the account config that handles this, or I need to use `agents bind` explicitly.","thinkingSignature":"fdb24086658e39c6dcd66c5aa531b4aa20ccebfa070fb5d4f2b7027a34bece20"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_ozia8a4zr5tr_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"grep -A 20 \"agents bind\\|binding\\|telegram.*agentId\" /home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw/docs/channels/telegram.md 2>/dev/null | head -80"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":21575,"output":532,"cacheRead":18779,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":40886,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775961292738,"responseId":"062a37cda7505cbc334fdb5ae2412464"}}
{"type":"message","id":"e0be3689","parentId":"a1bad921","timestamp":"2026-04-12T02:35:09.400Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_ozia8a4zr5tr_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"**Persistent ACP topic binding**: Forum topics can pin ACP harness sessions through top-level typed ACP bindings:\n\n    - `bindings[]` with `type: \"acp\"` and `match.channel: \"telegram\"`\n\n    Example:\n\n    ```json5\n    {\n      agents: {\n        list: [\n          {\n            id: \"codex\",\n            runtime: {\n              type: \"acp\",\n              acp: {\n                agent: \"codex\",\n                backend: \"acpx\",\n                mode: \"persistent\",\n                cwd: \"/workspace/openclaw\",\n              },\n            },\n          },\n        ],\n--\n      bindings: [\n        {\n          type: \"acp\",\n          agentId: \"codex\",\n          match: {\n            channel: \"telegram\",\n            accountId: \"default\",\n            peer: { kind: \"group\", id: \"-1001234567890:topic:42\" },\n          },\n        },\n      ],\n      channels: {\n        telegram: {\n          groups: {\n            \"-1001234567890\": {\n              topics: {\n                \"42\": {\n                  requireMention: false,\n                },\n              },\n            },\n--\n  - `channels.telegram.groups.<id>.topics.<threadId>.*`: per-topic overrides (group fields + topic-only `agentId`).\n  - `channels.telegram.groups.<id>.topics.<threadId>.agentId`: route this topic to a specific agent (overrides group-level and binding routing).\n- `channels.telegram.groups.<id>.topics.<threadId>.groupPolicy`: per-topic override for groupPolicy (`open | allowlist | disabled`).\n- `channels.telegram.groups.<id>.topics.<threadId>.requireMention`: per-topic mention gating override.\n- top-level `bindings[]` with `type: \"acp\"` and canonical topic id `chatId:topic:topicId` in `match.peer.id`: persistent ACP topic binding fields (see [ACP Agents](/tools/acp-agents#channel-specific-settings)).\n- `channels.telegram.direct.<id>.topics.<threadId>.agentId`: route DM topics to a specific agent (same behavior as forum topics).\n- `channels.telegram.execApprovals.enabled`: enable Telegram as a chat-based exec approval client for this account.\n- `channels.telegram.execApprovals.approvers`: Telegram user IDs allowed to approve or deny exec requests. Optional when `channels.telegram.allowFrom` or a direct `channels.telegram.defaultTo` already identifies the owner.\n- `channels.telegram.execApprovals.target`: `dm | channel | both` (default: `dm`). `channel` and `both` preserve the originating Telegram topic when present.\n- `channels.telegram.execApprovals.agentFilter`: optional agent ID filter for forwarded approval prompts.\n- `channels.telegram.execApprovals.sessionFilter`: optional session key filter (substring or regex) for forwarded approval prompts.\n- `channels.telegram.accounts.<account>.execApprovals`: per-account override for Telegram exec approval routing and approver authorization.\n- `channels.telegram.capabilities.inlineButtons`: `off | dm | group | all | allowlist` (default: allowlist).\n- `channels.telegram.accounts.<account>.capabilities.inlineButtons`: per-account override.\n- `channels.telegram.commands.nativeSkills`: enable/disable Telegram native skills commands.\n- `channels.telegram.replyToMode`: `off | first | all` (default: `off`).\n- `channels.telegram.textChunkLimit`: outbound chunk size (chars).\n- `channels.telegram.chunkMode`: `length` (default) or `newline` to split on blank lines (paragraph boundaries) before length chunking.\n- `channels.telegram.linkPreview`: toggle link previews for outbound messages (default: true).\n- `channels.telegram.streaming`: `off | partial | block | progress` (live stream preview; default: `partial`; `progress` maps to `partial`; `block` is legacy preview mode compatibility). Telegram preview streaming uses a single preview message that is edited in place.\n- `channels.telegram.mediaMaxMb`: inbound/outbound Telegram media cap (MB, default: 100).\n- `channels.telegram.retry`: retry policy for Telegram send helpers (CLI/tools/actions) on recoverable outbound API errors (attempts, minDelayMs, maxDelayMs, jitter).\n- `channels.telegram.network.autoSelectFamily`: override Node autoSelectFamily (true=enable, false=disable). Defaults to enabled on Node 22+, with WSL2 defaulting to disabled.\n- `channels.telegram.network.dnsResultOrder`: override DNS result order (`ipv4first` or `verbatim`). Defaults to `ipv4first` on Node 22+.\n- `channels.telegram.network.dangerouslyAllowPrivateNetwork`: dangerous opt-in for trusted fake-IP or transparent-proxy environments where Telegram media downloads resolve `api.telegram.org` to private/internal/special-use addresses outside the default RFC 2544 benchmark-range allowance.\n- `channels.telegram.proxy`: proxy URL for Bot API calls (SOCKS/HTTP).\n--\n- access control: `dmPolicy`, `allowFrom`, `groupPolicy`, `groupAllowFrom`, `groups`, `groups.*.topics.*`, top-level `bindings[]` (`type: \"acp\"`)\n- exec approvals: `execApprovals`, `accounts.*.execApprovals`\n- command/menu: `commands.native`, `commands.nativeSkills`, `customCommands`\n- threading/replies: `replyToMode`\n- streaming: `streaming` (preview), `blockStreaming`\n- formatting/delivery: `textChunkLimit`, `chunkMode`, `linkPreview`, `responsePrefix`\n- media/network: `mediaMaxMb`, `timeoutSeconds`, `retry`, `network.autoSelectFamily`, `network.dangerouslyAllowPrivateNetwork`, `proxy`"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":21,"aggregated":"**Persistent ACP topic binding**: Forum topics can pin ACP harness sessions through top-level typed ACP bindings:\n\n    - `bindings[]` with `type: \"acp\"` and `match.channel: \"telegram\"`\n\n    Example:\n\n    ```json5\n    {\n      agents: {\n        list: [\n          {\n            id: \"codex\",\n            runtime: {\n              type: \"acp\",\n              acp: {\n                agent: \"codex\",\n                backend: \"acpx\",\n                mode: \"persistent\",\n                cwd: \"/workspace/openclaw\",\n              },\n            },\n          },\n        ],\n--\n      bindings: [\n        {\n          type: \"acp\",\n          agentId: \"codex\",\n          match: {\n            channel: \"telegram\",\n            accountId: \"default\",\n            peer: { kind: \"group\", id: \"-1001234567890:topic:42\" },\n          },\n        },\n      ],\n      channels: {\n        telegram: {\n          groups: {\n            \"-1001234567890\": {\n              topics: {\n                \"42\": {\n                  requireMention: false,\n                },\n              },\n            },\n--\n  - `channels.telegram.groups.<id>.topics.<threadId>.*`: per-topic overrides (group fields + topic-only `agentId`).\n  - `channels.telegram.groups.<id>.topics.<threadId>.agentId`: route this topic to a specific agent (overrides group-level and binding routing).\n- `channels.telegram.groups.<id>.topics.<threadId>.groupPolicy`: per-topic override for groupPolicy (`open | allowlist | disabled`).\n- `channels.telegram.groups.<id>.topics.<threadId>.requireMention`: per-topic mention gating override.\n- top-level `bindings[]` with `type: \"acp\"` and canonical topic id `chatId:topic:topicId` in `match.peer.id`: persistent ACP topic binding fields (see [ACP Agents](/tools/acp-agents#channel-specific-settings)).\n- `channels.telegram.direct.<id>.topics.<threadId>.agentId`: route DM topics to a specific agent (same behavior as forum topics).\n- `channels.telegram.execApprovals.enabled`: enable Telegram as a chat-based exec approval client for this account.\n- `channels.telegram.execApprovals.approvers`: Telegram user IDs allowed to approve or deny exec requests. Optional when `channels.telegram.allowFrom` or a direct `channels.telegram.defaultTo` already identifies the owner.\n- `channels.telegram.execApprovals.target`: `dm | channel | both` (default: `dm`). `channel` and `both` preserve the originating Telegram topic when present.\n- `channels.telegram.execApprovals.agentFilter`: optional agent ID filter for forwarded approval prompts.\n- `channels.telegram.execApprovals.sessionFilter`: optional session key filter (substring or regex) for forwarded approval prompts.\n- `channels.telegram.accounts.<account>.execApprovals`: per-account override for Telegram exec approval routing and approver authorization.\n- `channels.telegram.capabilities.inlineButtons`: `off | dm | group | all | allowlist` (default: allowlist).\n- `channels.telegram.accounts.<account>.capabilities.inlineButtons`: per-account override.\n- `channels.telegram.commands.nativeSkills`: enable/disable Telegram native skills commands.\n- `channels.telegram.replyToMode`: `off | first | all` (default: `off`).\n- `channels.telegram.textChunkLimit`: outbound chunk size (chars).\n- `channels.telegram.chunkMode`: `length` (default) or `newline` to split on blank lines (paragraph boundaries) before length chunking.\n- `channels.telegram.linkPreview`: toggle link previews for outbound messages (default: true).\n- `channels.telegram.streaming`: `off | partial | block | progress` (live stream preview; default: `partial`; `progress` maps to `partial`; `block` is legacy preview mode compatibility). Telegram preview streaming uses a single preview message that is edited in place.\n- `channels.telegram.mediaMaxMb`: inbound/outbound Telegram media cap (MB, default: 100).\n- `channels.telegram.retry`: retry policy for Telegram send helpers (CLI/tools/actions) on recoverable outbound API errors (attempts, minDelayMs, maxDelayMs, jitter).\n- `channels.telegram.network.autoSelectFamily`: override Node autoSelectFamily (true=enable, false=disable). Defaults to enabled on Node 22+, with WSL2 defaulting to disabled.\n- `channels.telegram.network.dnsResultOrder`: override DNS result order (`ipv4first` or `verbatim`). Defaults to `ipv4first` on Node 22+.\n- `channels.telegram.network.dangerouslyAllowPrivateNetwork`: dangerous opt-in for trusted fake-IP or transparent-proxy environments where Telegram media downloads resolve `api.telegram.org` to private/internal/special-use addresses outside the default RFC 2544 benchmark-range allowance.\n- `channels.telegram.proxy`: proxy URL for Bot API calls (SOCKS/HTTP).\n--\n- access control: `dmPolicy`, `allowFrom`, `groupPolicy`, `groupAllowFrom`, `groups`, `groups.*.topics.*`, top-level `bindings[]` (`type: \"acp\"`)\n- exec approvals: `execApprovals`, `accounts.*.execApprovals`\n- command/menu: `commands.native`, `commands.nativeSkills`, `customCommands`\n- threading/replies: `replyToMode`\n- streaming: `streaming` (preview), `blockStreaming`\n- formatting/delivery: `textChunkLimit`, `chunkMode`, `linkPreview`, `responsePrefix`\n- media/network: `mediaMaxMb`, `timeoutSeconds`, `retry`, `network.autoSelectFamily`, `network.dangerouslyAllowPrivateNetwork`, `proxy`","cwd":"/home/travis/Lookitry/Lookitry/sammy"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775961309398}}
{"type":"message","id":"7ddd9857","parentId":"e0be3689","timestamp":"2026-04-12T02:35:24.853Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the routing mechanism. For direct DMs, I need to look at `channels.telegram.direct.<id>.topics.<threadId>.agentId`. \n\nActually wait, let me re-examine. The doc mentions `channels.telegram.direct.<id>.topics.<threadId>.agentId` for routing DM topics. But for a simple DM (not a forum topic), there might be a simpler approach.\n\nLet me look at the `direct` section in the schema more carefully. I saw `direct` and `dms` in the schema. Let me check if there's a way to set a default agent for direct DMs.\n\nActually, let me think about this differently. Looking at the `allowFrom: [\"1049458877\"]` in the `rebecca` account, this only allows Sam's messages. And Sam IS reaching me (Sammy default agent). So the routing is: DM → default agent (sammy) → authorized sender check passes.\n\nThe issue is that the rebecca account bot (Rebecca_lookitrybot) is routing to the default agent (sammy) instead of to the rebecca agent.\n\nLet me look at the `direct` field in the schema again. From the docs:\n- `channels.telegram.direct.<id>.topics.<threadId>.agentId`: route DM topics to a specific agent\n\nThis suggests that DMs can be routed to specific agents via the `direct` config. But the `direct` object might need to be configured with sender-based routing.\n\nActually, wait. Let me look at the `agents bind` CLI command docs. It says:\n- `openclaw agents bind --agent work --bind telegram:ops`\n\nThis suggests you can bind an agent to a specific Telegram bot/context. The `:ops` part might refer to a specific bot username or account.\n\nLet me try using the CLI to understand the current bindings, then figure out how to make the rebecca bot route to rebecca agent.","thinkingSignature":"0723b1ab7d42acfc519f441f8265d4fa3d5ea7cfe6e94bb7cb4a12d8458f2cb7"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_u2ng75etj420_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cd /home/travis/Lookitry/openclaw && openclaw agents list 2>/dev/null || echo \"checking agents...\""}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":23337,"output":461,"cacheRead":18779,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":42577,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775961309402,"responseId":"062a37ddea5a1eed990b999eb7b98da2"}}
